y are not. On the other side, some are really good and helpful and understanding. &#10;If the government can show us that it's capable of doing the job properly and in a useful manner (ticking boxes on a worksheet to keep bureaucrats happy is not useful) that benefits the home educators then we might be more willing. &#10;At the moment, to register when one doesn't have to is merely to invite hassle with no net benefit. I don't think there are many who would opt to do that if given the choice. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="798" language="en" documentId="952" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Thienz" date="06 November 2009 7:00pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6747787" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="7" thumbsDown="0" origId="952" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="389"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="390" end="622"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="623" end="798"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>